[1] Hong Kong
Date: Sun, 22 Jun 2003
From: Luiz Jacintho da Silva <luiz_jacintho@uol.com.br>
Source: Xinhuanet 21 Jun 2003 18:00:56 [edited]


First cholera case in 2003 reported in HK
-----------------------------------------
The Department of Health of Hong Kong on Sat, 21 Jun 2003 urged the public
to be on guard against foodborne infections following the confirmation of a
case of co-infection with _Vibrio cholerae_ and _Vibrio parahaemolyticus_.

The case, which is the first reported cholera case in Hong Kong in 2003,
involved a 39-year-old woman who suffered from watery diarrhea, abdominal
pain, and fever. She is now in stable condition in a hospital, according to
the health department. In addition to bacteria causing cholera, _Vibrio
parahaemolyticus_, a type of bacteria causing fever and diarrhea, was also
found in the same specimen from the patient, the department said, adding
the source of infection has not been identified yet.

A spokesman for the department said the best way to prevent cholera and
other foodborne diseases is to observe good personal, food, and
environmental hygiene at all times. 4 confirmed cholera cases were
reported in 2002, among which 2 were imported and 2 were local cases.

