[5] Uganda (Cholera and Dysentery)
Date: 18 May 2003
From: Malimbo Mugagga <malimbom@hotmail.ocm>
Source: Uganda Weekly Epidemiological Newsletters [edited]


19 Week of 2003 (Week ending 11 May 2003)
--------------------------
Kasese reported a sharp increase in cholera cases, from 9 cases last week
to 55 cases this week. A relatively small increase in cholera cases was
also recorded in Bundibugyo, from 46 cases last week to 51 cases (with 2
deaths) this week. Kabarole reported 8 cases.

Dysentery cases occurred in 98 percent (55/56) of the districts with 48
percent (27/55) of them reporting an increase compared to last week.
Overall cases increased by 157 compared to last week. Districts with
leading numbers of dysentery cases were Gulu (130 cases), Moroto (90
cases), Arua (80 cases), Adjumani (71 cases), and Bundibugyo (63 cases).
The districts that experienced the biggest increases in cases compared to
last week were Gulu (from 67 to 130), Moroto (from 45 to 90), Adjumani
(from 36 to71), Kitgum (from 12 to 38) and Kalangala (from 7 to 29).

20th Week of 2003 (Week ending 18 May 2003)
----------------------------
A cholera epidemic is continuing in 3 districts. Bundibugyo reported the
highest number cases (53 cases with 3 deaths), followed by Kasese (36
cases) and Kabarole (26 cases). Kabarole recorded the highest increase in
cases (by 18) compared to last week while Kasese recorded a reduction by 19
cases. In Bundibugyo, cases increased by 2.

Dysentery cases occurred in 98 percent (55/56) of the districts with 64
percent (36/55) of them reporting a reduction in cases compared to last
week. Districts with leading numbers of dysentery cases were Arua (85
cases), Bundibugyo (59 cases), Kotido (59 cases), Kampala (59 cases),
Adjumani (48 cases), Nebbi (46 cases), and Gulu (46 cases). Overall, cases
reduced by 311 compared to last week.

