[7] Haiti
Date: 17 Jun 2003
From: Marianne Hopp <mjhopp12@yahoo.com>
Source: WHO Outbreak Reports [edited]
<http://www.who.int/csr/don/2003_06_17a/en/>


Typhiod in Haiti - Update
-------------------------
As of 30 May 2003, 200 cases of typhoid and 40 deaths have been reported by
the WHO Regional Office for the Americas (PAHO) and the Ministry of Health,
Haiti. 3 cases have been laboratory-confirmed.

The outbreak started in Apr 2003 during the dry season and affected remote
villages in the Grand Bois Area, bordering the Dominican Republic. These
villages lack access to health care facilities and to safe water; all water
points in the area showed a maximum level of _E. coli_ pollution. Most of
the deaths occurred in persons who had no access to health care facilities.

In May 2003, PAHO and the Ministry of Health sent a team to investigate and
control the epidemic, including: sampling water points, establishing mobile
clinics, laboratory testing of cases, providing health education, and
organizing the response at the local level.

******
[8] Zimbabwe
Date: 25 Jun 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AllAfrica.com and The Herald (Harare) [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200306250096.html>


Chinhoyi Diarrhoea Death Toll Hits 5
-------------------------------------------
One more person died from diarrhea in Chinhoyi yesterday, bringing to 5 the
number of people who have succumbed to the water-borne disease in the
Mashonaland West provincial capital since last week.

There have been allegations that the town's water is unfit for human
consumption, but town officials have dismissed the claims. But officials
at the provincial medical directorate in Chinhoyi yesterday confirmed the
town's water had indeed tested unfit for human consumption.

"That we can confirm, recent tests proved the water was not fit for human
consumption," said Mashonaland West provincial medical director, Dr
Wenceslas Nyamayaro. 4 people died last week after allegedly
drinking contaminated water.

More than 500 cases of diarrhea, mostly affecting under-5-year-olds, were
reported in Chinhoyi last week, and Dr Nyamayaro attributed these to
contaminated water.

He also said there was a possibility that sewerage water might have leaked
into a river, which feeds into the dam which supplies the town with
water. The Chinhoyi municipality is said to have only 4 out of the 14
chemicals required for water treatment. But council officials dismissed
the allegations, saying they were doing all what was required to treat
water. "We have enough water treatment chemicals and the stocks are here,"
said an official.

